gle-pulse\nshape. The rms pulsed fraction is high and increases from about 40% to 50%. We\nfind no dependence of pulse shape or fraction on energy. These results suggest\nthat multiple hotspots, possibly possessing temperature gradients, emerged at\noutburst-onset, and shrank as the outburst decayed. We detect 84 faint bursts\nwith \\nicer, having a strong preference for occurring close to the surface\nemission pulse maximum the first time this phenomenon is detected in such a\nlarge burst sample. This likely implies a very low altitude for the burst\nemission region, and a triggering mechanism connected to the surface active\nzone. Finally, our radio observations at several epochs and multiple\nfrequencies reveal no evidence of pulsed or burst-like radio emission.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 14 Jan 2022 15:18:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-01-26"}
